Eutetranychus banksi
is a polyphagous species widely distributed (Nearctic, Neotropical, Palearctic, and Oriental regions) and has recently been reported for the first time in the Mediterranean region in Portugal (
Gonçalves et al ., 2002
) and Spain (
Garcia et al ., 2003
). It develops under dry, low RH conditions and at temperatures close to 27°C ( Dean, 1959 ); the optimum range of development is at 28- 31°C (
Badii et al ., 2003
). On citrus feeding symptoms of the Texas citrus mite are similar to those of the citrus red mite,
P. citri (
Jeppson et al ., 1975
)
.
